WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en-US

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.620
GEOFF BENNETT: In a recent report,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:01.620 --> 00:00:06.540
Judy Woodruff examined how the loss of&nbsp;
thousands of local newspapers across&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:06.540 --> 00:00:10.620
the country is depriving communities of&nbsp;
some of the glue that holds them together.

00:00:10.620 --> 00:00:15.900
Tonight, she looks at how some news outlets&nbsp;
are managing to hang on, and whether what&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:15.900 --> 00:00:21.240
they're doing is sustainable. It's part of&nbsp;
her ongoing series America at a Crossroads.

00:00:21.240 --> 00:00:28.740
JUDY WOODRUFF: Just after dawn most Thursdays,&nbsp;
Anne Adams takes to the winding mountain roads of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:28.740 --> 00:00:35.232
Western Virginia, delivering a local newspaper,&nbsp;
The Recorder, to small stores and coffee shops.

00:00:35.232 --> 00:00:36.600
ANNE ADAMS, Editor and Publisher,&nbsp;
The Recorder: I will set one aside&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:36.600 --> 00:00:37.545
when I get back over to the office.

00:00:37.545 --> 00:00:42.060
JUDY WOODRUFF: But Adams isn't just the&nbsp;
delivery person. She is also the owner,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:42.060 --> 00:00:46.080
editor and publisher of this&nbsp;
paper that covers three counties,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:46.080 --> 00:00:49.620
including two of the most&nbsp;
sparsely populated in the state.

00:00:49.620 --> 00:00:54.468
And like many local news editors, she's&nbsp;
closely connected to the community.

00:00:54.468 --> 00:00:58.080
ANNE ADAMS: Folks need to know what's&nbsp;
going on. They need to know their&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:58.080 --> 00:01:02.325
neighbors. They need to know what what's&nbsp;
happening, how their money is being spent.

00:01:02.325 --> 00:01:07.440
JUDY WOODRUFF: The paper's Highland County&nbsp;
office is nestled in the midst of the Allegheny&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:07.440 --> 00:01:13.800
Mountains in Monterey, Virginia, a small&nbsp;
one-stoplight town of about 160 residents.

00:01:13.800 --> 00:01:19.740
Adams says people in this tight-knit&nbsp;
community not only suggest story ideas,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:19.740 --> 00:01:21.948
but also hold her to account.

00:01:21.948 --> 00:01:25.980
ANNE ADAMS: You can be shopping, and dropping&nbsp;
the kids off at school, and they're like,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:25.980 --> 00:01:31.485
we think you crossed the line there or&nbsp;
not sure that was the right way to put it.

00:01:31.485 --> 00:01:33.540
JUDY WOODRUFF: For much of the country's history,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:33.540 --> 00:01:40.440
local newspapers played a key role in uniting&nbsp;
communities, highlighting common challenges and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:40.440 --> 00:01:45.888
events that tie people together, like high&nbsp;
school sports and local political races.

00:01:45.888 --> 00:01:51.120
ANNE ADAMS: We have always had a really good&nbsp;
-- got a grapevine gossip network here. But,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:51.120 --> 00:01:53.640
well, we will dig into it and&nbsp;
find out what's really going on,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:53.640 --> 00:01:56.520
what's really happening and report&nbsp;
that. And then it settles down.

00:01:56.520 --> 00:02:01.500
Without a newspaper to do that, I just&nbsp;
feel like folks would not have the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:01.500 --> 00:02:06.000
right information. I think they would be less&nbsp;
engaged, less apt to vote, less apt to care.

00:02:06.000 --> 00:02:10.500
JUDY WOODRUFF: But that's become the&nbsp;
reality for many Americans over the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:10.500 --> 00:02:16.080
last two decades. About 2,500 local&nbsp;
newspapers, a quarter of the total,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:16.080 --> 00:02:22.500
have folded since 2005, according to Northwestern&nbsp;
University's Medill School of Journalism.

00:02:22.500 --> 00:02:29.220
In that same period, newspaper revenue&nbsp;
has plunged from $50 billion to 20&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:29.220 --> 00:02:34.140
billion. News organizations that have&nbsp;
been able to survive are operating on&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:34.140 --> 00:02:39.720
razor-thin margins. One-fifth of U.S.&nbsp;
residents now live in news deserts,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:39.720 --> 00:02:45.408
where residents have very limited access to&nbsp;
credible and comprehensive news and information.

00:02:45.408 --> 00:02:48.720
ANNE ADAMS: So they did&nbsp;
scrub a times past look-back,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:48.720 --> 00:02:52.905
even in the '30s. And that's a&nbsp;
feature that we still publish today.

00:02:52.905 --> 00:02:53.928
JUDY WOODRUFF: That you still do today.

00:02:53.928 --> 00:02:54.165
ANNE ADAMS: Yes.

00:02:54.165 --> 00:02:59.628
JUDY WOODRUFF: Adams, who is only the 10th&nbsp;
publisher of the paper, took over in 2007.

00:02:59.628 --> 00:03:03.585
ANNE ADAMS: But look at these tiny little&nbsp;
headlines. Graphic designers today would go crazy.

00:03:03.585 --> 00:03:08.100
JUDY WOODRUFF: The Recorder has helped&nbsp;
hold this community with its long,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:08.100 --> 00:03:15.000
proud history together for 146 years.&nbsp;
It's done so mainly by selling ads and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:15.000 --> 00:03:20.760
subscriptions at a time when so many local&nbsp;
newspapers across the country have collapsed.

00:03:20.760 --> 00:03:25.359
But it may not be financially&nbsp;
sustainable in the long run.

00:03:25.359 --> 00:03:27.480
ANNE ADAMS: The cost of printing has gone up. The&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:27.480 --> 00:03:30.285
cost of paper has gone up. The&nbsp;
cost of postage has gone up.

00:03:30.285 --> 00:03:32.160
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, can you venture a guess,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:32.160 --> 00:03:36.168
an educated guess as to how long&nbsp;
you can keep this model going?

00:03:36.168 --> 00:03:41.700
ANNE ADAMS: Well, as long as I'm alive&nbsp;
and doing this. I mean, I always say,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:41.700 --> 00:03:44.325
we're not going to kill it off on my&nbsp;
watch. We will do whatever we have to do.

00:03:44.325 --> 00:03:50.340
JUDY WOODRUFF: In 2017, Adams gambled and&nbsp;
more than doubled the newsstand price from&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:50.340 --> 00:03:56.160
$2 to $5. And it was just five issues&nbsp;
away from folding during the pandemic,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:56.160 --> 00:04:00.960
when its readers stepped in with donations&nbsp;
to keep the printing presses going.

00:04:00.960 --> 00:04:06.420
All this has paid off, most visibly&nbsp;
in The Recorder breaking the news in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:06.420 --> 00:04:12.840
2014 of the proposed Atlantic Coast&nbsp;
Pipeline, a 600-mile natural gas line&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:12.840 --> 00:04:18.528
that would have cut through three states and&nbsp;
potentially had huge environmental impacts.

00:04:18.528 --> 00:04:21.960
ANNE ADAMS: I remember everybody kept saying,&nbsp;
why are you bothering? You can't fight&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:22.620 --> 00:04:25.200
a company like Dominion,&nbsp;
especially not in Virginia.

00:04:26.220 --> 00:04:30.840
We just kept hammering away at them.&nbsp;
And we got the privilege of being the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:30.840 --> 00:04:33.105
first to report when they shut the project down.

00:04:33.105 --> 00:04:35.880
JUDY WOODRUFF: But many local newspapers lack the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:35.880 --> 00:04:41.220
manpower to do that kind of reporting.&nbsp;
Newsroom employment has been slashed&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:41.220 --> 00:04:48.240
by 60 percent since 2005, turning many&nbsp;
small publications into ghost newspapers.

00:04:48.240 --> 00:04:54.000
In Jackson, Mississippi, staff at The&nbsp;
Clarion-Ledger, owned by the Gannett chain,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:54.000 --> 00:04:57.915
has suffered repeated rounds&nbsp;
of cuts in the last 15 years.

00:04:57.915 --> 00:04:59.160
MARY MARGARET WHITE, CEO,&nbsp;
Mississippi Today: And there&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:59.160 --> 00:05:01.800
really was just a lack of Statehouse reporting.

00:05:01.800 --> 00:05:06.240
JUDY WOODRUFF: Mary Margaret White&nbsp;
is the CEO of Mississippi Today,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:06.240 --> 00:05:13.479
a nonprofit digital news source launched&nbsp;
in 2016 that's run by donations and grants.

00:05:13.479 --> 00:05:16.080
MARY MARGARET WHITE: Some big issues&nbsp;
were coming through the legislature,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:16.080 --> 00:05:21.585
and there was no one there to cover them. And that&nbsp;
was really the early days of Mississippi Today.

00:05:21.585 --> 00:05:27.639
JUDY WOODRUFF: It's become an exemplar of now&nbsp;
rapid growth in these alternative news outlets.

00:05:27.639 --> 00:05:32.040
MARY MARGARET WHITE: In early days,&nbsp;
making a case for journalism as&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:32.040 --> 00:05:36.300
philanthropy was really a long and&nbsp;
hard conversation. It was just so&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:36.300 --> 00:05:41.700
new to so many people that you would give&nbsp;
philanthropically to the press, to media.

00:05:41.700 --> 00:05:44.820
And now six, seven years later,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:44.820 --> 00:05:50.700
people are really beginning to understand&nbsp;
the value of journalism to our democracy,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:50.700 --> 00:05:56.400
the value of it to local communities, and&nbsp;
that it is a worthwhile cause to support.

00:05:56.400 --> 00:05:59.335
Last year, I'm so proud, we&nbsp;
brought in more than $400,000.

00:05:59.335 --> 00:06:01.059
JUDY WOODRUFF: My gosh. Wow.

00:06:01.059 --> 00:06:03.045
MARY MARGARET WHITE: And&nbsp;
that's from everyday people.

00:06:03.045 --> 00:06:08.820
JUDY WOODRUFF: Mississippi Today publishes the&nbsp;
names of its donors online, and is partially&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:08.820 --> 00:06:15.009
funded by a venture philanthropy, the American&nbsp;
Journalism Project based in Washington, D.C.

00:06:15.009 --> 00:06:16.140
SARABETH BERMAN, CEO, American&nbsp;
Journalism Project: We think&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:16.140 --> 00:06:19.785
we're at the front end of building a&nbsp;
new generation of news organizations.

00:06:19.785 --> 00:06:23.220
JUDY WOODRUFF: The project was&nbsp;
established four years ago,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:23.220 --> 00:06:27.060
and now helps support 41&nbsp;
newsrooms across the country.

00:06:27.060 --> 00:06:29.923
Sarabeth Berman is the CEO.

00:06:29.923 --> 00:06:36.120
SARABETH BERMAN: We have seen over the last&nbsp;
several years new digital nonprofit news&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:36.120 --> 00:06:40.200
organizations that are really fundamentally&nbsp;
reimagining how we finance local news.

00:06:40.200 --> 00:06:46.140
We used to use advertising to finance local&nbsp;
news. That has largely disappeared. About&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:46.140 --> 00:06:50.580
80 percent of advertising revenue has&nbsp;
disappeared in the last two decades. And&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:50.580 --> 00:06:55.860
these organizations are really thinking&nbsp;
of their financial structure in the same&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:55.860 --> 00:06:59.400
way we think of other organizations that&nbsp;
are really essential to our communities,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:59.400 --> 00:07:03.600
like libraries and museums and other&nbsp;
institutions that stitch us together.

00:07:03.600 --> 00:07:07.125
MAN: If you're trying to&nbsp;
register to vote, can't do it.

00:07:07.125 --> 00:07:11.040
JUDY WOODRUFF: Mississippi Today's&nbsp;
reporters cover policy and politics,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:11.040 --> 00:07:15.600
which are livelier than usual in&nbsp;
this, a statewide election year.

00:07:15.600 --> 00:07:19.425
MAN: Because I want to see our&nbsp;
election system change in our state.

00:07:19.425 --> 00:07:21.660
JUDY WOODRUFF: Last month, we caught up with their&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:21.660 --> 00:07:26.160
small team of reporters covering the&nbsp;
candidates at the Neshoba County Fair.

00:07:26.160 --> 00:07:29.400
And we spoke with residents&nbsp;
who say they have grown to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:29.400 --> 00:07:32.904
rely on Mississippi Today's digital-only platform.

00:07:32.904 --> 00:07:35.040
WILL SIMMONS, Mississippi Resident: And&nbsp;
I don't agree with everything they write,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:35.040 --> 00:07:40.680
but it is -- I mean, a lot of it&nbsp;
is -- it seems like they're -- it's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:40.680 --> 00:07:42.945
just pretty straight facts, a lot of what they do.

00:07:42.945 --> 00:07:46.140
JUDY WOODRUFF: Now one of the&nbsp;
largest newsrooms in the state,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:46.140 --> 00:07:49.860
Mississippi Today won a Pulitzer&nbsp;
Prize earlier this year.

00:07:49.860 --> 00:07:56.160
Reporter Anna Wolfe's investigation "The&nbsp;
Backchannel" exposed the state's diversion&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:56.160 --> 00:08:00.840
of millions of federal welfare dollars&nbsp;
intended to help some of the poorest&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:00.840 --> 00:08:06.300
people in the country instead directed&nbsp;
to political supporters, such as former&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:06.300 --> 00:08:11.160
football star Brett Favre to build a&nbsp;
volleyball stadium at his alma mater.

00:08:11.160 --> 00:08:13.920
ANNA WOLFE, Mississippi Today:&nbsp;
I think I'm probably on that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:13.920 --> 00:08:16.545
story up to at least 100 public records requests.

00:08:16.545 --> 00:08:20.868
JUDY WOODRUFF: Wolfe estimated she worked&nbsp;
on the story on and off for five years.

00:08:20.868 --> 00:08:25.740
ANNA WOLFE: So you think about the time that&nbsp;
it takes to draft those and see them through&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:25.740 --> 00:08:29.460
the process of actually being able&nbsp;
to get your hands on those records,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:29.460 --> 00:08:33.060
and people might not realize how long it takes,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:33.060 --> 00:08:39.420
and then might not realize the investment&nbsp;
that is required to do that kind of work.

00:08:39.420 --> 00:08:44.640
JUDY WOODRUFF: At times, the news outlet's&nbsp;
reporting has angered Republican leadership.

00:08:45.240 --> 00:08:50.280
Just last month, former Mississippi&nbsp;
Governor Phil Bryant sued the news outlet,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:50.280 --> 00:08:55.620
charging its employees defamed him&nbsp;
in public comments. The lawsuit does&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:55.620 --> 00:08:59.880
not appear to challenge the veracity of&nbsp;
the reporting. While Mississippi Today&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:59.880 --> 00:09:05.100
has focused heavily on state House and&nbsp;
investigative reporting, Sarabeth Berman&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:05.100 --> 00:09:11.023
acknowledges that new nonprofit newsrooms also&nbsp;
need to build up trust in their communities.

00:09:11.023 --> 00:09:15.480
SARABETH BERMAN: Mississippi Today, last year&nbsp;
during the Jackson water crisis, was out there&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:15.480 --> 00:09:22.560
providing people with just the basic tools that&nbsp;
they need to be able to navigate this crisis,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:22.560 --> 00:09:28.200
information about how to get water and what to&nbsp;
do if you if you don't have access to good water.

00:09:28.200 --> 00:09:30.420
And by providing people with&nbsp;
that kind of information,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:30.420 --> 00:09:34.485
you begin to build trust with them that&nbsp;
you are there and you're on their side.

00:09:34.485 --> 00:09:38.880
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well, the nonprofit model&nbsp;
is showing promise in urban settings,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:38.880 --> 00:09:45.780
economic realities persist for small local&nbsp;
newspapers that still depend on subscriptions&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:45.780 --> 00:09:48.798
and advertising, like The Recorder in Virginia.

00:09:48.798 --> 00:09:52.365
PENNY ABERNATHY, Northwestern University:&nbsp;
The traditional news model has just vanished.

00:09:52.365 --> 00:09:57.360
JUDY WOODRUFF: Northwestern University's Penny&nbsp;
Abernathy has done extensive research on local&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:57.360 --> 00:10:04.080
journalism. She posits that more than 90 percent&nbsp;
of all news organizations are still commercially&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:04.080 --> 00:10:10.483
based and news organizations benefiting from&nbsp;
nonprofit dollars are geographically uneven.

00:10:10.483 --> 00:10:15.180
PENNY ABERNATHY: It leaves smaller communities&nbsp;
kind of at a loss as to how do you go about&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:15.180 --> 00:10:21.000
getting that initial ignition that brings&nbsp;
people together and helps them understand&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:21.000 --> 00:10:26.745
that they can do this, that they can raise&nbsp;
that money to support local news operations.

00:10:26.745 --> 00:10:29.100
JUDY WOODRUFF: She says one solution might&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:29.100 --> 00:10:32.940
be using public dollars to&nbsp;
help local newsrooms survive,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:32.940 --> 00:10:38.683
subsidies for hiring reporters and for local&nbsp;
businesses that advertise in the local paper.

00:10:38.683 --> 00:10:43.080
PENNY ABERNATHY: There just isn't sufficient&nbsp;
subscriber revenue to pay the bills. And,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:43.080 --> 00:10:48.345
of course, there's not sufficient philanthropic&nbsp;
dollars to lift them up over the profit margin.

00:10:48.345 --> 00:10:53.323
JUDY WOODRUFF: The challenges ahead are&nbsp;
great, and the stakes are very high.

00:10:53.323 --> 00:10:58.560
PENNY ABERNATHY: Increasingly, I'm worried that&nbsp;
we're evolving into a nation of journalistic&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:58.560 --> 00:11:04.980
haves and have-nots. That has huge implications&nbsp;
for not only our democracy, but for our society.

00:11:04.980 --> 00:11:08.580
How do we come together around a common set of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:08.580 --> 00:11:12.300
facts to solve the issues that are&nbsp;
confronting us in the 21st century?

00:11:12.300 --> 00:11:16.020
JUDY WOODRUFF: For the "PBS&nbsp;
NewsHour," I'm Judy Woodruff&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:16.020 --> 00:11:18.840
in Jackson, Mississippi, and Monterey, Virginia.

